“Athens” (pp. 1–2; poem, 4 stanzas, entitled “Athens” in pencil; 
                                    specifically, draft of stanzas 1–4, with stanzas 2, 3, and 4 numbered as such by Ruskin; 
                                    following stanza 4, bottom p. 2, Ruskin added the gloss, 
                                    
                                        
                                        “For Continuation [i.e., of “Athens”] see page 14”).

“It was an eve of summer, mild” (64v–65r; poem, untitled, lines numbered 890–920 by Ruskin; 
                                    combined with the 8 lines, “So broadly stretched in sapphire sheet”, 
                                    and entitled by Collingwood, not by Ruskin, as “Lago Maggiore”).

“So broadly stretched in sapphire sheet” (78v; poem, untitled; lines numbered 1369–76 by Ruskin; 
                                        appended to the end of “It was an eve of summer mild” [“Lago Maggiore”] by W. G. Collingwood 
                                        for the version of that poem printed in Poems [1891] and reprinted by the editors of the Library Edition).

“January” (pp. 114r–14v, positioned between stanzas 11 and 12 of 
                                    “As I was walking round by Peckham rye”, which wraps around this work; 
                                poem, titled by Ruskin).
